# Cursor Rules for Documentation Standards

## Documentation Requirements

### JSDoc Docstrings are Mandatory

All exported and public functions, components, types, interfaces, and classes MUST have JSDoc docstrings. This ensures maintainability and improves code documentation coverage.

### What Needs Docstrings

1. **React Components** (both default and named exports)
   - Include component purpose, props description, and return type
   - Document any complex behavior or side effects

2. **Functions** (exported and internal helper functions)
   - Include parameter descriptions with `@param` tags
   - Include return value descriptions with `@returns` tags
   - Document any side effects or exceptions

3. **Type Definitions and Interfaces**
   - Document the purpose and structure
   - Document each property when helpful for complex types

4. **Classes**
   - Document the class purpose
   - Document all public methods and properties
   - Document constructor parameters

5. **Constants and Exported Objects**
   - Document their purpose and usage when not self-explanatory

### JSDoc Format Standards

Use the following format for all docstrings:

```typescript
/**
 * Brief description of what the function/component/type does.
 * Additional detailed description if needed.
 * 
 * @param {Type} paramName - Description of the parameter
 * @returns {Type} Description of the return value
 * @example
 * // Usage example if helpful
 */
```

### Component Documentation Template

For React components, use this format:

```typescript
/**
 * Component description explaining its purpose and behavior.
 * Include any important details about props, state, or side effects.
 * 
 * @param {Object} props - Component props
 * @param {Type} props.propName - Description of prop
 * @returns {JSX.Element} Description of what the component renders
 */
export default function ComponentName({ propName }: PropsType) {
  // ...
}
```

### Type Documentation Template

For types and interfaces:

```typescript
/**
 * Description of what this type represents and its purpose.
 * @typedef {Object} TypeName
 * @property {Type} propertyName - Description of the property
 */
type TypeName = {
  propertyName: Type;
};
```

### Function Documentation Template

For helper functions:

```typescript
/**
 * Brief description of what the function does.
 * 
 * @param {Type} paramName - Description of the parameter
 * @returns {Type} Description of the return value
 */
function functionName(paramName: Type): ReturnType {
  // ...
}
```

### When Creating New Code

- **ALWAYS** add JSDoc docstrings when creating new functions, components, or types
- **ALWAYS** update docstrings when modifying function signatures or component props
- **ALWAYS** document exported constants and objects that aren't self-explanatory

### When Modifying Existing Code

- **ALWAYS** update docstrings if you change function signatures, component props, or type definitions
- **ALWAYS** ensure docstrings accurately reflect the current implementation
- **ALWAYS** add docstrings to any new exported functions or components you add

### Code Review Checklist

Before submitting code, ensure:
- [ ] All exported functions have JSDoc docstrings
- [ ] All React components have JSDoc docstrings
- [ ] All type definitions and interfaces have JSDoc docstrings
- [ ] All `@param` tags are accurate and complete
- [ ] All `@returns` tags are present and accurate
- [ ] Docstrings match the current implementation

### Examples

#### Good Component Documentation

```typescript
/**
 * Navigation bar component with responsive menu, dark mode toggle, and active section highlighting.
 * Includes desktop and mobile menu variants with intersection observer for section tracking.
 * @returns {JSX.Element} A navigation bar component
 */
export default function Navbar() {
  // ...
}
```

#### Good Type Documentation

```typescript
/**
 * Represents a work experience entry with role, company, duration, and achievements.
 * @typedef {Object} Experience
 * @property {string} role - The job title or role name
 * @property {string} company - The company name
 * @property {string} duration - The time period (e.g., "2020 - 2022")
 * @property {string[]} achievements - Array of achievement descriptions
 */
type Experience = {
  role: string;
  company: string;
  duration: string;
  achievements: string[];
};
```

#### Good Function Documentation

```typescript
/**
 * Validates an email address format and sets error state if invalid.
 * @param {string} email - Email address to validate
 * @returns {boolean} True if email is valid, false otherwise
 */
const validateEmail = (email: string): boolean => {
  // ...
};
```

### Enforcement

- Code without proper docstrings should be flagged during code review
- New code should not be merged without complete documentation
- When refactoring, ensure docstrings are updated to match the new implementation

### Benefits

Maintaining comprehensive docstrings:
- Improves code maintainability
- Helps new developers understand the codebase
- Enables better IDE autocomplete and IntelliSense
- Supports automated documentation generation
- Ensures consistent documentation coverage across the project

